First and foremost, the Electoral College provides a level of certainty in determining the outcome of the election. In the 2012 election, for example, President Obama received 61.7% of the electoral vote compared to only 51.3% of the popular vote. This discrepancy shows that the Electoral College system often results in a decisive victory for the winning candidate, avoiding potential disputes over the popular vote.

