Subject: In Support of Retaining the Electoral College

Dear Senator [Senator's Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for retaining the Electoral College as the method of electing the President of the United States. While there are valid arguments made for changing to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College serves the best interests of our nation, as it ensures fairness, stability, and a truly representative democracy.

Firstly, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. The winning candidate's share of the Electoral College consistently exceeds their share of the popular vote, which is essential in preventing disputes over the election results. This avoids potential legal battles and ensures a smooth transition of power. As we saw in the 2012 election, President Obama received 61.7% of the electoral vote compared to only 51.3% of the popular vote. This disparity is a result of the winner-take-all system and creates a landslide victory in each state, thereby reducing the likelihood of an electoral tie.

Secondly, the Electoral College ensures that every region of our country has a say in the election. No single region has enough electoral votes to determine the outcome, forcing candidates to have broad-based national appeal. This fosters a presidency that represents the interests of the entire nation, rather than one focused solely on a specific region. By encouraging candidates to campaign in all states, regardless of size, the Electoral College prevents the disenfranchisement of voters and promotes a more inclusive democracy.

Additionally, the Electoral College directs candidates to focus their efforts on swing states, thereby engaging citizens in a more meaningful way. In these states, voters pay closer attention to the campaign and become more informed about the candidates and their policies. By having swing states decide the election, we ensure that the most thoughtful and engaged voters have the opportunity to shape the outcome. This encourages candidates to listen to the concerns of all Americans and address the issues that are relevant to a diverse range of voters.

Moreover, the Electoral College provides a balancing mechanism for the influence of large states. While the popular vote may heavily favor candidates who campaign predominantly in densely populated areas, the Electoral College ensures that candidates must appeal to voters across the entire country. By giving more attention to large states, the Electoral College restores balance and prevents candidates from neglecting the interests of smaller states and rural areas.

Finally, the Electoral College eradicates the need for run-off elections, which can be time-consuming and create further complexities in our election process. The Electoral College invariably produces a clear winner, avoiding the need for divisive and potentially costly run-offs. This streamlining of the election process contributes to the stability and efficiency of our democracy.

In conclusion, the Electoral College serves as a crucial component of our democratic system, providing certainty, fairness, and broad-based representation. It ensures the interests of all regions are considered, drives candidate engagement in swing states, balances the influence of large states, and avoids the need for run-off elections. Rather than dismissing the Electoral College, I urge you to support its retention and continue to uphold the principles upon which it was established.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I trust that you will consider the points raised in this letter and make decisions that serve the best interests of our great nation.

Sincerely,

