"Dear [State Senator],

I am writing to express my support for the Electoral College and urge you to consider the advantages it brings to our presidential election process. While some argue for a change to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College serves an important purpose and should be kept intact.

One of the main reasons to retain the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome it provides. In a popular vote system, disputes over the outcome of an election are more likely to occur. The winner of the popular vote does not always align with the winner of the Electoral College, as seen in the 2000 election. The Electoral College ensures that the winning candidate's share of electoral votes exceeds their share of the popular vote, reducing the likelihood of disputes.

Furthermore, the Electoral College ensures that the president represents the entire nation, not just certain regions. With the requirement for a presidential candidate to have trans-regional appeal, no single region has enough electoral votes to elect a president. This encourages candidates to campaign across different states and listen to the concerns of voters from various regions. It prevents candidates with only regional appeal from being successful presidents and makes sure that everyone feels represented.

