One of the main reasons to keep the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome it provides. In a close election, disputes can arise over the popular vote count, as we saw in the 2000 election. However, the Electoral College ensures that the winning candidate's share of electoral votes exceeds their share of the popular vote. This means that the overall outcome is more decisive and less likely to be contested.

