"Dear Senator [Name],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as the method of electing the President of the United States. While it is widely regarded as an anachronism and there are calls for a change to direct popular vote, I believe that there are practical reasons for retaining the Electoral College system.

Firstly, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. A dispute over the outcome of an Electoral College vote is less likely than a dispute over the popular vote. This is because the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College invariably exceeds their share of the popular vote. Additionally, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes in most states creates a landslide electoral-vote victory, reducing the chances of a tie in the nationwide electoral vote.

Secondly, the Electoral College ensures that the President has trans-regional appeal. No single region in the country has enough electoral votes to elect a president. This means that a candidate with only regional appeal is unlikely to be successful. The Electoral College encourages candidates to campaign across the country and consider the interests of all regions, preventing some voters from feeling disenfranchised.

Thirdly, the Electoral College focuses campaign efforts on swing states. In these toss-up states, voters pay closer attention to the campaign and have the opportunity to listen to the competing candidates. These voters are likely to be the most thoughtful and informed, and they should be the ones to decide the election.

Fourthly, the Electoral College restores some of the weight in the political balance that large states lose due to the mal-apportionment of the Senate. Presidential candidates pay more attention to large states in their campaigns, considering their interests and concerns. This helps to ensure that the voices of voters in large states are heard and not overshadowed by smaller states.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections. In situations where no candidate receives a majority of the popular vote, the Electoral College invariably produces a clear winner. This eliminates the pressure and complications that could arise from run-off elections.

While there are arguments against the Electoral College, such as the potential for voters in states dominated by one party to feel their vote doesn't matter, it is important to note that no single vote swings a national election. Voters participate in presidential elections to express their political preferences, not with the expectation that their vote alone will decide the outcome.

Overall, the Electoral College system has practical reasons for its retention. It provides certainty, trans-regional appeal, focus on swing states, balance for large states, and avoids run-off elections. It is important to consider these factors when discussing the election of the President of the United States.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

