Dear [Senator's Name],

I am writing to express my support for the Electoral College as the method of selecting the President of the United States. While there are valid arguments for changing to an election by popular vote, I believe that the Electoral College system has several practical benefits that should be considered.

Firstly, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. With the winner-take-all system in each state, even a slight plurality in a state can create a landslide electoral-vote victory. This ensures that the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College exceeds their share of the popular vote, reducing the likelihood of a dispute over the outcome. In the 2012 election, President Obama received 61.7 percent of the electoral vote compared to only 51.3 percent of the popular vote.

Secondly, the Electoral College promotes a president with trans-regional appeal. No region has enough electoral votes to elect a president, meaning that candidates need to appeal to a broad range of voters across different states. This prevents a candidate with only regional appeal from winning the presidency, ensuring that the new president represents the interests of all regions and making them more likely to be a successful leader.

Additionally, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes encourages candidates to focus their campaign efforts on swing states. Voters in these states are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign, as they know that their votes will decide the outcome. They are likely to be the most thoughtful voters and should be the ones to determine the election. This system ensures that candidates allocate their resources and attention based on the needs and concerns of swing states.

Moreover, the Electoral College restores some balance between large and small states. As per the mal-apportionment of the Senate, large states lose weight in the political balance. The Electoral College compensates for this by giving larger states more attention from presidential candidates during campaigns. This ensures that candidates address the needs and concerns of citizens residing in both big and small states.

Finally, the Electoral College eliminates the need for run-off elections. In cases where no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast, pressure for run-off elections can complicate the electoral process. The Electoral College invariably produces a clear winner, preventing such complications and ensuring a smooth transition of power.

While some argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states where their vote is unlikely to impact the outcome, it is important to note that voters in presidential elections are people who wish to express their political preference, not individuals who believe that their vote alone can decide an election. In the 2012 election, despite this perceived issue, approximately half of the eligible American population still exercised their right to vote.

In conclusion, the Electoral College system has practical benefits that should be taken into consideration. It provides certainty of outcome, ensures a president with trans-regional appeal, allows for focused attention on swing states, balances the influence of large and small states, and prevents the need for run-off elections. While there are arguments for changing to an election by popular vote, I believe that the Electoral College remains a fair and effective system for selecting the President of the United States.

Thank you for considering my perspective. I trust that you will take the time to carefully consider the merits of the Electoral College when deciding on this important issue. Please feel free to reach out to me if you have any further questions or if there is any additional information I can provide.

Sincerely,

